-- Regression: REG-02 crash-canary for IRON_HIR_STMT_ASSIGN
-- (incl. compound assign += / -= / *=).
--
-- **Motivating Incident.** Phase 37-02's collect_mono_enums_node AST
-- walker missed elif_conds[] recursion for Iron_IfStmt. The same
-- walker-incompleteness class can re-emerge for any statement kind.
-- Iron_Assign (plain assign) and the compound-assign forms lower to
-- the same IRON_HIR_STMT_ASSIGN case in lower_stmt. Walker regressions
-- that fail to recurse into the RHS expression silently drop the
-- right-hand side from the lowered LIR -- meaning the target variable
-- keeps its old value while the test still compiles. Phase 66 added
-- -Werror=switch-enum to catch missing cases at compile time, and
-- _Static_assert guards on the Iron_ExprNode common prefix. This
-- canary is the runtime regression net for IRON_HIR_STMT_ASSIGN.
--
-- **Layout Diagram.** Iron_Assign carries
--   { span, kind, target, value, op_kind }
-- where op_kind is ASSIGN_SIMPLE / ASSIGN_ADD / ASSIGN_SUB / ASSIGN_MUL
-- / ASSIGN_DIV / ASSIGN_MOD. Walker cases that fail to recurse into
-- `value` drop the RHS expression; cases that ignore `op_kind` produce
-- wrong semantics for compound assigns (e.g. treating += as =).
--
-- **Fix Summary.** Phase 67-08 added this fixture as a REG-02 crash
-- canary. Exercises both simple assign and the three compound forms
-- (+=, -=, *=) that this codebase uses. CI integration: runs in both
-- Debug and Release via Phase 66-04's build-and-test-release job.
--
-- **Severity.** H (regression potential) -- a missing assign-case
-- recursion would silently produce wrong numeric output, which is
-- exactly the "passes compile, wrong runtime" failure mode the Phase
-- 37-02 motivating bug caused.

func main() {
  var x = 10
  x = x + 5           -- simple assign: 15
  x += 7              -- compound add: 22
  x *= 2              -- compound mul: 44
  x -= 4              -- compound sub: 40
  var y = x
  y = y + x           -- simple assign, RHS uses captured local: 80
  println("x: {x}")
  println("y: {y}")
}
